ope, fortune, and death, integrating the aspect of Machaut's multimedia art that differentiates him from his contemporaries' treatment of similar thematic issues: music. In restoring the centrality of music in Machaut's poetics, arguing that his words cannot be truly understood or appreciated without the additional layers of meaning created in their musicalization, Leach makes a compelling argument that musico-literary performance occupied a special place in the courts of fourteenth-century France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh  amusico-literary, fourteenth-century french literature, Machaut’s multi-media art, french poetry, ars nova style, late medieval music.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170486440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501704864423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501704864/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles